 Corona survey -- t10 Risk factors of post COVID-19 condition attributed to COVID-19 disease in people aged 50+ in Europe and Israel -- t11 Sex differences in activity and mental health changes following the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic in Europe -- tPart III Employment and labour market during the pandemic -- t12 Did the pandemic change retirement trends? -- t13 Short-time employment aid during the COVID-19 lockdown: Shortand long-run effectiveness -- t14 Work interruptions and medium-term labour market outcomes of older workers during the COVID-19 pandemic -- t15 What is the future of (remote) work? -- t16 Changes in work performance and work losses during the COVID-19 pandemic -- t17 Containment measures and job loss: Evidence from SHARE CORONA surveys -- t18 Internet use during the pandemic -- tPart IV Income and economic situation -- t19 Persistence of economic stress during the COVID-19 pandemic -- t20 Effects of COVID-19-related economic support on household financial distress -- t21 How the first wave of the pandemic affected household finances -- t22 Financial hardship during the COVID-19 pandemic -- t23 Pandemic lockdowns: The role of economic and demographic structures -- tPart V Social and geographical patterns -- t24 Receiving care at home during the COVID-19 pandemic: Revisiting the situations of care recipients 18 months after the outbreak of SARS-CoV-2 -- t25 Effects of lockdown measures on receiving home care during the COVID-19 pandemic: A subgroup analysis -- t26 Prayer frequency and COVID-19 vaccine hesitancy among people aged 50+: A comparison of European regions -- t27 Two Nordic countries with different approaches to handling the COVID-19 pandemic: A comparison of Sweden and Denmark -- t28 Epidemiological control measures and subjective age among people aged 50 or older -- tPart VI Housing and living arrangements -- t29 Do intergenerational co-residence and multigenerational housing arrangements increase the risk of COVID-19 morbidity? Findings from SHARE -- t30 Housing conditions, living arrangements, and mental well-being of Europeans aged 50+: How the COVID- 19 pandemic made a difference -- t31 Housing, living arrangements, and contagion among Europeans aged 50+ -- t32 Health status of older Europeans living alone: The role of living arrangements, healthcare, and social supports in the COVID-19 pandemic0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe COVID-19 pandemic posed a major threat to the well-being of older Europeans. Its economic and social effects, however, varied across countries. This multidisciplinary book presents the first results of analyses that combined the renowned longitudinal database of SHARE with new data from two telephone surveys that were uniquely conducted during the pandemic. The analyses address important policy-related issues, such as: Did social distancing destabilize family and social support networks? Did the pandemic increase health, social and economic inequality? Who had to forego essential health care because of the pandemic? Did lockdown affect one's physical and mental health? Did the shift towards remote work affect workload and well-being? Were different housing conditions related to the spread of the virus?  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAlternde Gesellschaft. 4aCorona. 4aGesundheitszustand. 4aSHARE. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / Microeconomics.2bisacsh  aCovid-19.  aEurope.  aSHARE.  aageing societies.  aeconomics.  ahealth status.  asocial policy.1 aAbramowska-Kmon, Anita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbramo